<section xml:id="sec-precalc-factor" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Factoring</title>

  <p>
    Factoring is one of the most important algebra skills for calculus.
    Many problems in limits, derivatives, and integrals require expressions
    to be simplified before any calculus ideas can be applied.
    In this section, we review the most common factoring techniques,
    starting from very basic patterns and gradually building toward
    the types of expressions that appear in calculus problems.
  </p>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
  <subsection xml:id="ssec-factor-gcf">
    <title>Factoring Out a Greatest Common Factor</title>

    <p>
      The first and most important factoring technique is factoring out
      the greatest common factor.
      If every term in an expression shares a common factor,
      that factor can be factored out.
    </p>

    <principle xml:id="pr-factor-gcf">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If every term of an expression contains a factor <m>a</m>, then
        </p>
        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
ab + ac &amp; = &amp; a(b + c)
\end{array}
        </me>
      </statement>
    </principle>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Factor <m>6x + 12</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Both terms share a factor of <m>6</m>.
        </p>
        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
6x + 12 &amp; = &amp; 6(x + 2)
\end{array}
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Factor <m>4x^2 + 8x</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Both terms share a factor of <m>4x</m>.
        </p>
        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
4x^2 + 8x &amp; = &amp; 4x(x + 2)
\end{array}
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Factor <m>-3x^3 + 6x^2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Both terms share a factor of <m>3x^2</m>.
          Factoring out a negative sign is often helpful.
        </p>
        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
-3x^3 + 6x^2 &amp; = &amp; -3x^2(x - 2)
\end{array}
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <remark>
      <p>
        Always check for a greatest common factor first.
        Many factoring mistakes come from skipping this step.
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
  <subsection xml:id="ssec-factor-difference-squares">
    <title>Difference of Squares</title>

    <p>
      One of the most common factoring patterns is the difference of squares.
      This pattern appears frequently in limits and rational expressions.
    </p>

    <principle xml:id="pr-difference-squares">
      <statement>
        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
a^2 - b^2 &amp; = &amp; (a - b)(a + b)
\end{array}
        </me>
      </statement>
    </principle>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Factor <m>x^2 - 16</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Recognize <m>16 = 4^2</m>.
        </p>
        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
x^2 - 16 &amp; = &amp; (x - 4)(x + 4)
\end{array}
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Factor <m>9x^2 - 25</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Rewrite each term as a square.
        </p>
        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
9x^2 - 25 &amp; = &amp; (3x)^2 - 5^2 \\
          &amp; = &amp; (3x - 5)(3x + 5)
\end{array}
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Simplify <m>\dfrac{x^2 - 9}{x - 3}</m> for <m>x \neq 3</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Factor the numerator.
        </p>
        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\dfrac{x^2 - 9}{x - 3}
&amp; = &amp;
\dfrac{(x - 3)(x + 3)}{x - 3} \\[0.6em]
&amp; = &amp;
x + 3
\end{array}
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>


    <remark>
      <p>
        The sum of squares <m>a^2 + b^2</m> does not factor over the real numbers.
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
  <subsection xml:id="ssec-factor-perfect-squares">
    <title>Perfect Square Trinomials</title>

    <p>
      Some trinomials arise from squaring a binomial.
      Recognizing these patterns allows quick factoring.
    </p>

    <principle xml:id="pr-perfect-square">
      <statement>
        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
a^2 + 2ab + b^2 &amp; = &amp; (a + b)^2 \\[0.6em]
a^2 - 2ab + b^2 &amp; = &amp; (a - b)^2
\end{array}
        </me>
      </statement>
    </principle>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Factor <m>x^2 + 6x + 9</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The middle term matches <m>2ab</m> with <m>a = x</m> and <m>b = 3</m>.
        </p>
        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
x^2 + 6x + 9 &amp; = &amp; (x + 3)^2
\end{array}
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Factor <m>x^2 - 10x + 25</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
x^2 - 10x + 25 &amp; = &amp; (x - 5)^2
\end{array}
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
<subsection xml:id="ssec-factor-general-trinomials">
  <title>Factoring General Trinomials Using the AC Method</title>

  <p>
    Not all trinomials factor easily by inspection.
    For expressions of the form <m>ax^2 + bx + c</m>,
    the <em>AC method</em> provides a systematic way to factor.
    This method is especially useful when the leading coefficient
    is not equal to 1, and it works equally well when it is.
  </p>

  <insight xml:id="pr-ac-method">
    <statement>
      <p>
        To factor <m>ax^2 + bx + c</m> using the AC method:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>Compute the product <m>ac</m>.</li>
        <li>Find two numbers whose product is <m>ac</m> and whose sum is <m>b</m>.</li>
        <li>Rewrite the middle term using these two numbers.</li>
        <li>Factor by grouping.</li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </insight>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Factor <m>x^2 + 5x + 6</m> using the AC method.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Step 1: Identify <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m>.
      </p>

      <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
a = 1, &amp; b = 5, &amp; c = 6
\end{array}
      </me>

      <p>
        Step 2: Compute <m>ac</m>.
      </p>

      <me>
        ac = 1 \cdot 6 = 6.
      </me>

      <p>
        Step 3: Find two numbers that multiply to <m>6</m> and add to <m>5</m>.
      </p>

      <me>
        2 \quad \text{and} \quad 3
      </me>

      <p>
        Step 4: Rewrite the middle term and factor by grouping.
      </p>

      <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
x^2 + 5x + 6
&amp; = &amp;
x^2 + 2x + 3x + 6 \\[0.6em]
&amp; = &amp;
x(x + 2) + 3(x + 2) \\[0.6em]
&amp; = &amp;
(x + 2)(x + 3)
\end{array}
      </me>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Factor <m>x^2 - x - 12</m> using the AC method.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Step 1: Identify <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m>.
      </p>

      <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
a = 1, &amp; b = -1, &amp; c = -12
\end{array}
      </me>

      <p>
        Step 2: Compute <m>ac</m>.
      </p>

      <me>
        ac = 1 \cdot (-12) = -12.
      </me>

      <p>
        Step 3: Find two numbers that multiply to <m>-12</m> and add to <m>-1</m>.
      </p>

      <me>
        -4 \quad \text{and} \quad 3
      </me>

      <p>
        Step 4: Rewrite the middle term and factor by grouping.
      </p>

      <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
x^2 - x - 12
&amp; = &amp;
x^2 - 4x + 3x - 12 \\[0.6em]
&amp; = &amp;
x(x - 4) + 3(x - 4) \\[0.6em]
&amp; = &amp;
(x - 4)(x + 3)
\end{array}
      </me>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <remark>
    <p>
      The AC method always works when a trinomial factors over the real numbers.
      With practice, you may recognize factors quickly, but this method provides
      a dependable fallback when guessing is difficult.
    </p>
  </remark>
</subsection>

